06281nam a22010695i 9783110755626DE-B159720220524034747.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220524t20222022gw     fo  d z      eng d  a2021945784  a97831107556267 a10.1515/97831107556262doi  a(DE-B1597)586150  a(OCoLC)1294426081  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE00aDS96b.C85 2022 4aDS96b.C85 2022 7aHIS0370102bisacsh04a935/.06222300aCulture and Ideology under the Seleukids :bUnframing a Dynasty /ced. by Eva Anagnostou-Laoutides, Stefan Pfeiffer. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (XII, 360 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe volume offers a timely (re-)appraisal of Seleukid cultural dynamics. While the engagement of Seleukid kings with local populations and the issue of “Hellenization” are still debated, a movement away from the Greco-centric approach to the study of the sources has gained pace. Increasingly textual sources are read alongside archaeological and numismatic evidence, and relevant near-eastern records are consulted.Our study of Seleukid kingship adheres to two game-changing principles: 1. We are not interested in judging the Seleukids as “strong” or “weak” whether in their interactions with other Hellenistic kingdoms or with the populations they ruled. 2. While appreciating the value of the social imaginaries approach (Stavrianopoulou, 2013), we argue that the use of ethnic identity in antiquity remains problematic.Through a pluralistic approach, in line with the complex cultural considerations that informed Seleukid royal agendas, we examine the concept of kingship and its gender aspects; tensions between centre and periphery; the level of “acculturation” intended and achieved under the Seleukids; the Seleukid-Ptolemaic interrelations. As rulers of a multi-cultural empire, the Seleukids were deeply aware of cultural politics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aSeleucidsxHistory. 0aSeleucids. 4aDiadochen. 4aHellenismus. 4aKultur - Ideologien. 4aSeleukiden. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh  aHellenism.  aSeleukid Ideology.  aSeleukid kingship.  acultural interface under the Seleukids.1 aAnagnostou-Laoutides, Eva, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAnagnostou-Laoutides, Eva, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBeaulieu, Paul-Alain, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrüggemann, Thomas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCoşkun, Altay, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDumke, Gunnar R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHunter, Daniel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLisle, Christopher de, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMairs, Rachel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcAuley, Alex, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcKechnie, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMehl, Andreas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMichel, Patrick M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOgden, Daniel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOlszewski, Marek T., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPfeiffer, Stefan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPfeiffer, Stefan, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aTrundle, Matthew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.l